commit_message:
Remove hardcoded reference to keystone /v2 API

Neutron handshake in Nova will allow /v3 url in the review
that this one depends on. So we can use the IDENTITY_API_VERSION
instead of hard coding the /v2 API in nova.conf's
[neutron]admin_auth_url config option.

Change-Id: I9d005a6a16b28ccd1a21ac3c23e25be409c87319

commit_message:
Gate failure due to introduction of new WSME 0.8.0

Many of the changes on gate are failing because of
Bad Request error. The reason for this is the request
accepts some fields whereas the entire dictionary is
getting passed without applying any filter. This
patch solves the problem. A new WSME version 0.8.0 was
introduced today, which seems to be the cause of this
problem.

http://osdir.com/ml/openstack-dev/2015-08/msg01687.html

Change-Id: I6d40889683449995df7bd7ebcdf755991cef43ef
Closes-bug: #1488687

commit_message:
Read affinity from environment

This patch allows a user to set the number of containers per host for
each type of container that has a default affinity greater than 1 for an
AIO build.

Currently this list is:
 * keystone
 * galera
 * rabbit_mq
 * horizon
 * repo

For example, one could set NUM_keystone_CONTAINERS=1 before running an
AIO to ensure that only one keystone container is built.

Change-Id: If90704a50414150ca37584e1f823ba0e85e287ac
Partially-Implements: blueprint split-aio-gates
(cherry picked from commit 39409db9b9caea199fd61110f348c0be209e6754)

commit_message:
Proper deprecation for Session.get_token()

Session.get_token() wasn't properly deprecated since the deprecation
was only mentioned in the docstring. Proper deprecation requires use
of warnings/debtcollector and documentation.

Also, changed a test to use the non-deprecated function instead where
the test wasn't checking that the deprecated function worked.

bp deprecations

Change-Id: I3d421b35554d58476281e037f90ab9b48e82730a

Configure space reservation on NetApp Data ONTAP

backends to be thick or thin provisioned.

subject: Unsafe operations must not act on the symlink
revisions:
[{'number': 1, 'created': '2015-07-25 04:10:44.000000000', 'files': ['specs/in_progress/symlinks.rst'], 'message': "Unsafe operations must not act on the symlink

I don't see how we can do it in an eventually consistent system.

And without specific handling it seems like:

With the post-as-copy option it'll just COPY the target object and write it
over the symlink.

With fast post we'll write the .meta file with the symlink.

I don't think we can HEAD every POST because it might be a symlink - so we'd
have to have some behavior on the object-server to reject write over symlink -
which isn't going to work all the time (handoff).

Discuss.

Change-Id: Id96cd64dd5830f03365f90eee76c064767f3b570
"}]
commit_message:
Unsafe operations must not act on the symlink

I don't see how we can do it in an eventually consistent system.

And without specific handling it seems like:

With the post-as-copy option it'll just COPY the target object and write it
over the symlink.

With fast post we'll write the .meta file with the symlink.

I don't think we can HEAD every POST because it might be a symlink - so we'd
have to have some behavior on the object-server to reject write over symlink -
which isn't going to work all the time (handoff).

Discuss.

Change-Id: Id96cd64dd5830f03365f90eee76c064767f3b570

commit_message:
Handle a skipped test without a reason message

This commit fixes a bug in subunit-trace where if a test is skipped
but does not have a reason associated with the skip it would stack
trace. This checks for the existence of a reason before trying to
use it.

Change-Id: I14dd9fbb40a8c232431e5042aa46f7e521e15311

commit_message:
Replace conductor proxying calls with the new VolumeUsage object

This change replace current conductor proxying for db.vol_usage_update()
by instead making use of the brand new VolumeUsage object.

Necessary changes are made to conductor manager to continue work with
the change to use dot notation in compute_utils.usage_volume_info().

Related to blueprint liberty-objects

Change-Id: Icc1caf2e0aa0c88bee044ffce9dcdcee6434de47

commit_message:
test/(functional/probe):Replace python print operator with print function (pep H233, py33)

'print' function is compatible with 2.x and 3.x python versions
Link : https://www.python.org/dev/peps/pep-3105/

Python 2.6 has a __future__ import that removes print as language syntax,
letting you use the functional form instead

commit_message:
Enable password support for vnc session

Enable password support for vnc session. This is to avoid
allowing an attacker to connect to the remote host as no
authentication is required to access this service. The
default vnc password is uuid of the instance, and this feature
can be enabled by setting the enable_vnc_password in nova.conf

Change-Id: I5a875d9921edff6c85ccb5a27c8a28e6bf3432d5
Closes-Bug: 1450294

commit_message:
Add Quota Enforcement API

This commit adds the quota enforcement API.  When emplemented, enforce()
will return without exception if a new resource can be created without
exceeding a quota limit.  enforce() will raise an exception if the
creation needs to be blocked due to the effective quota.  A detailed
error message is created for both the log and the response body of
the create request.

Change-Id: Iaf2a3a3e5960e84c3fe7d9d2becf1cc32b788833
Partially-implements: blueprint quota-support-on-barbican-resources

revisions:
[{'number': 2, 'created': '2015-08-25 19:09:37.000000000', 'files': ['ceilometer_powervm/tests/compute/virt/powervm/test_inspector.py', 'ceilometer_powervm/compute/virt/powervm/inspector.py'], 'message': "Account for live migrated VMs

In PowerVM, when a VM is migrated, the 'metrics come with it'.  That
means that the metrics are cumulative and you can be assured that when
it is on a new host, its metrics are still valid.

This presents some complications.  The metrics are pulled from the host.
To determine rates, we ask the host for the previous sample and the
current.  Previously we had assumed that if the previous sample was
None, it must be a new VM so all the traffic from the current is 'new'.

With live migration taken into account, we can not do that.  There may
be months of CPU, Network and Storage data in that VMs metrics.  This
really skews the metrics in undesirable ways.

This change set will skip instances (for a given inspection cycle) that
are in the current sample but not the previous.  This does lose a sample
cycle, but ensures that we maintain accurracy (which is more important).

Change-Id: Iba7f1287b3433acd8517947e01cbfa14fe93413c
"}]
commit_message:
Account for live migrated VMs

In PowerVM, when a VM is migrated, the 'metrics come with it'.  That
means that the metrics are cumulative and you can be assured that when
it is on a new host, its metrics are still valid.

This presents some complications.  The metrics are pulled from the host.
To determine rates, we ask the host for the previous sample and the
current.  Previously we had assumed that if the previous sample was
None, it must be a new VM so all the traffic from the current is 'new'.

With live migration taken into account, we can not do that.  There may
be months of CPU, Network and Storage data in that VMs metrics.  This
really skews the metrics in undesirable ways.

This change set will skip instances (for a given inspection cycle) that
are in the current sample but not the previous.  This does lose a sample
cycle, but ensures that we maintain accurracy (which is more important).

Change-Id: Iba7f1287b3433acd8517947e01cbfa14fe93413c

commit_message:
PowerVM Storage Inspector

This change set provides base support for the PowerVM compute inspector
to collect the storage devices.

Since PowerVM monitors storage metrics on the 'buses' (rather than a per
device) the metrics are reported based on the bus.  This may be a
virtual SCSI bus or a virtual Fibre Channel bus.

Change-Id: I704c7e79e825b7d5f0f8924c28d502ccbfb9330d

commit_message:
Moving the RefStack project from openstack-infra to Big Tent.

RefStack is a test result collection and reporting service to
support the DefCore testing process. It consumes the output of
DefCore mostly in the form of a Board-approved JSON document,
which it uses to determine whether a cloud has passed all the
tests required by the DefCore Guideline in question.

RefStack has been approved to move from stackforge to
openstack-infra [1]. However, there are increasing feedback
and general consensus of the Foundation staff is that RefStack
should be a Big Tent project.

RefStack has elected PTL and core members.  The core members
approve all code changes.  RefStack code is submitted and
reviewed using the OpenStack infrastructure [2].

RefStack has been running weekly meetings from the start of the
project. Meetings are held on Monday at 19:00 UTC and are open
to anyone that wants to attend. Our Weekly meeting agenda is
published at the meeting wiki [3].

The #refstack IRC channel on freenode is logged and the channel is
notified of such logging [4].

A RefStack server (refstack.openstack.org) will be hosted by
OpenStack Infra [5][6].

[1]https://review.openstack.org/#/c/205609/
[2]https://review.openstack.org/#/q/project:stackforge/refstack,n,z
[3]https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Meetings/Refstack
[4]http://eavesdrop.openstack.org/irclogs/%23refstack/
[5]https://review.openstack.org/#/c/188207/
[6[https://review.openstack.org/#/c/198869/

Change-Id: I2a9f029acc6908deb5486567eadb311b43dffbdb

commit_message:
RPCify rule_model

Previously the rule_model manipulated the methods of the
policy engine directly and maintained consistency between
the database and policy engine.  Once the API and policy
engine are running in separate processes, that will no
longer work.

This change introduces the RPC abstraction for the rule_model.
It also moves the maintanence of the policy engine and
database into the policy engine itself, effectively
creating a persistance later for the policy engine.

Also moved a few functions around in the policy engine
to make the layering clearer.

Partially-implements: blueprint dist-api-rpcify-rule
Change-Id: I2be8ef35dd9819036a24e617b3ad1aa268aa2782

subject: Include HTTP error codes in error_codes
revisions:
[{'number': 3, 'created': '2015-08-22 01:17:37.000000000', 'files': ['congress/exception.py', 'congress/api/webservice.py', 'congress/api/error_codes.py', 'congress/tests/api/test_error_codes.py'], 'message': 'Include HTTP error codes in error_codes

Previously, error_codes.py was used only at the API layer.  And
HTTP error codes were computed ad-hoc using a combination of
error_codes.py and exception types raised by policy engines and
datasources.

This exception architecture is especially troublesome now that
API models are communicating with policy engines/datasources
via RPC because more of the logic for errors is being pushed
into the policy-engine and datasources.  Thus when exceptions
are raised, they should really contain enough semantics for
the API layer to convert to HTTP error codes.

This change adds HTTP error codes to error_codes and adds
a constructor to the DataModelException that copies the
error_codes from a given exception.  In subsequent changes,
the policy-engine/datasources will raise exceptions with
the appropriate error_codes and the API will transform
them into DataModelExceptions with appropriate HTTP codes.

Partially-implements: blueprint dist-api-rpcify-row
Change-Id: Ic122a3ecd89ae3d9ccafce17d284a921b9b64f32
'}]
commit_message:
Include HTTP error codes in error_codes

Previously, error_codes.py was used only at the API layer.  And
HTTP error codes were computed ad-hoc using a combination of
error_codes.py and exception types raised by policy engines and
datasources.

This exception architecture is especially troublesome now that
API models are communicating with policy engines/datasources
via RPC because more of the logic for errors is being pushed
into the policy-engine and datasources.  Thus when exceptions
are raised, they should really contain enough semantics for
the API layer to convert to HTTP error codes.

This change adds HTTP error codes to error_codes and adds
a constructor to the DataModelException that copies the
error_codes from a given exception.  In subsequent changes,
the policy-engine/datasources will raise exceptions with
the appropriate error_codes and the API will transform
them into DataModelExceptions with appropriate HTTP codes.

Partially-implements: blueprint dist-api-rpcify-row
Change-Id: Ic122a3ecd89ae3d9ccafce17d284a921b9b64f32

subject: Prepare Policy Model API for RPC
revisions:
[{'number': 9, 'created': '2015-08-22 00:04:37.000000000', 'files': ['congress/tests/test_congress.py', 'congress/api/policy_model.py', 'congress/policy_engines/agnostic.py', 'congress/api/error_codes.py'], 'message': "Prepare Policy Model API for RPC

Previously the policy model API used Python pointers to the
policy engine for its implementation.  This won't work when
the API model is running in a different process than the
policy engine.  Also, the API model was responsible for
keeping the in-memory policy engine in sync with the database;
this is unnatural once the policy engine is running in
its own process and using its own database.

This change rewrites the policy model so that it uses
a fake RPC method instead of a direct Python reference to the
policy engine.  It also moves the database synchronization to
the policy engine.

Partially-implements: blueprint dist-api-rpcify-policy
Change-Id: I87116cc43bd280788bb810db6d668f0ca7f4b07a
"}]
commit_message:
Prepare Policy Model API for RPC

Previously the policy model API used Python pointers to the
policy engine for its implementation.  This won't work when
the API model is running in a different process than the
policy engine.  Also, the API model was responsible for
keeping the in-memory policy engine in sync with the database;
this is unnatural once the policy engine is running in
its own process and using its own database.

This change rewrites the policy model so that it uses
a fake RPC method instead of a direct Python reference to the
policy engine.  It also moves the database synchronization to
the policy engine.

Partially-implements: blueprint dist-api-rpcify-policy
Change-Id: I87116cc43bd280788bb810db6d668f0ca7f4b07a

subject: Make Resource.find more generically applicable
revisions:
[{'number': 4, 'created': '2015-08-25 17:09:14.000000000', 'files': ['openstack/tests/unit/test_resource.py', 'openstack/resource.py', 'openstack/tests/functional/compute/v2/test_flavor.py'], 'message': "Make Resource.find more generically applicable

The previous Resource.find was using query parameters of
id= and name= after directly attempting Resource.get_by_id.
In a few cases, this actually works, such as on Server.find
where it's able to accept the name= query parameter and
properly return a match. However, most other resources don't
work with those query parameters, so unless the find was done
by ID, there was very little chance of finding a match.

This change keeps mostly the same structure but does so without
using query parameters. It keeps the original Resource.get_by_id
to potentially find an immediate match, but if it needs to look
further it does so by making one request for all data and then
looks at both the name and id attributes in a loop to find a matching
resource.

This refactoring ends up fixing several outstanding bugs for
certain resources' find methods not working. It additionally
fixes a bug where searches by name would raise DuplicateResource
both when a single match existed, duplicate matches existed,
and also when no match existed. This was due to the baked in
query parameter logic and assumption that it was working causing
us to handle those responses differently than what they were
really signifying.

Change-Id: I4ae0599334b73b14a36a6f63bc8b26343abb1466
Closes-Bug: 1466174
Closes-Bug: 1384230
Closes-Bug: 1456317
Closes-Bug: 1455768
Closes-Bug: 1486705
"}]
commit_message:
Make Resource.find more generically applicable

The previous Resource.find was using query parameters of
id= and name= after directly attempting Resource.get_by_id.
In a few cases, this actually works, such as on Server.find
where it's able to accept the name= query parameter and
properly return a match. However, most other resources don't
work with those query parameters, so unless the find was done
by ID, there was very little chance of finding a match.

This change keeps mostly the same structure but does so without
using query parameters. It keeps the original Resource.get_by_id
to potentially find an immediate match, but if it needs to look
further it does so by making one request for all data and then
looks at both the name and id attributes in a loop to find a matching
resource.

This refactoring ends up fixing several outstanding bugs for
certain resources' find methods not working. It additionally
fixes a bug where searches by name would raise DuplicateResource
both when a single match existed, duplicate matches existed,
and also when no match existed. This was due to the baked in
query parameter logic and assumption that it was working causing
us to handle those responses differently than what they were
really signifying.

Change-Id: I4ae0599334b73b14a36a6f63bc8b26343abb1466
Closes-Bug: 1466174
Closes-Bug: 1384230
Closes-Bug: 1456317
Closes-Bug: 1455768
Closes-Bug: 1486705

Currently compute security_group_default_rules_client returns Response by
removing top key from Response.
For example-
 return service_client.ResponseBody(resp, body['security_group_default_rule'])

As service clients are in direction to move to Tempest-lib, all

One good example is Resource pagination links which are lost with current

Implements: blueprint method-return-value-and-move-service-clients-to-lib

commit_message:
Return complete resp from sec grp default rule client

Currently compute security_group_default_rules_client returns Response by
removing top key from Response.
For example-
 return service_client.ResponseBody(resp, body['security_group_default_rule'])

As service clients are in direction to move to Tempest-lib, all
service clients should return Response without any truncation.
One good example is Resource pagination links which are lost with current
way of return value. Resource pagination links are present in parallel
(not inside) to top key of Response.

This patch makes compute security_group_default_rules_client to return
complete Response body.

Change-Id: Ie39cb8a0d710c1412836f93ce6b3df60faad9f76
Implements: blueprint method-return-value-and-move-service-clients-to-lib

commit_message:
file: fix potential race condition in storing measure

We currently do open/mkdir/open in the case where the first open fails.
Though it might be rare, but it's possible that between mkdir and open a
rmdir occurs, and therefore the second open will fail again too.

So let's replace that by a infinite loop instead.

Change-Id: Iec65528415c5b8e832c173dda47815d4e2c943bb

commit_message:
Flavor created only when flavorid is an integer

Initially, when the "id" was set to non-integer
or non-UUID, the flavor was also created successfully.

Now, with this patch we are able to create a flavor
with "id" only.

commit_message:
default_schedule_zone should be a list of AZ(s)

Operator may have more than one AZ that they would like their
users to boot to by default. This also helps in the case as
described in the bug report where an operator may want to
specify all their AZ(s) *except* for one special AZ. So this
gives more power to the operators.

Since not all az's listed in default_schedule_zones list may be
available at the specific time, we should pick at random from
a subset of those that are actually available.

Note that we use a MultiStrOpt which will help keep the compatability
with the older config files.

DocImpact

Closes-Bug: #1474467
Change-Id: I5f69319b0a3c36043a04d4301dc0fac36b7d4170

commit_message:
storage: remove create_metric()

This changes the storage driver API so that there's no need to create
metric before adding metrics. We let the indexer be responsible for the
status of a metric to be existing or non existing, and we allow the
storage driver to create metric on the fly.

Pros:

1. Speeds up the metric creation process as we do not need to reach the
   storage to create a container + empty archives
2. Avoid us for a COMMIT/ROLLBACK step we would have to handle in the
   metric creation process, in the case where creating a metric either
   storage or indexer would fail – we would have to rollback the
   creation that did not fail.

Cons:

1. We now acknowledge that it's more difficult to have an autonomous
   storage driver working without an indexer. While this was no obvious
   before Gnocchi 1.0.0, it's getting pretty clear now that we don't
   want to bypass the indexer as it's anyway responsible for things such
   as RBAC. And we can anyway cache him.

This will help fixing bug #1483634 since we'll be able to create metric
only in the indexer, doing that in only one single transaction.

This change also handles correctly deletion of unprocessed measures for
metrics that has been deleted.

Change-Id: I81ff5ca5540a8a02d378c289bed611a1329f9325
Related-Bug: #1483634

revisions:
[{'number': 2, 'created': '2015-08-25 11:31:41.000000000', 'files': ['gnocchi/rest/__init__.py', 'gnocchi/tests/gabbi/gabbits/transformedids.yaml', 'gnocchi/tests/test_rest.py'], 'message': 'Introduce a resource id translation shim

In the openstack environment resource ids are a mismash of UUIDs
(yay!) and other things (boo!). When gnocchi receives a resource id
that is not a UUID, it drops it on the floor with a 400 error.

In some sense this is the exact right thing to do. In others it is
entirely impractical given the use context.

This change introduces a shim which accepts any string as a resource
id, either in the URL or in the Resource voluptuous Schema and does
a transformation on it to turn it into a UUID. That transformation
is:

* check if the string <= 255 in length (ValueError if not)
* create a uuid5 using RESOURCE_ID_NAMESPACE UUID and the string
* use the resulting UUID as the local id for the resource

This is a recommended form of creating URNs via rfc 4122
https://www.ietf.org/rfc/rfc4122.txt

The transform is done for both writes and reads. This is necessary
because we have no control over who or what is the the caller using
the API. Gnocchi users will expect to be able to access data in the
Gnocchi API by the IDs they are familiar with.

Doing things this way:

* keeps UUIDs as the primary identifiers internally
* requires no indexer-database migration (which a change in id
  structure would).
* is less intrusive than providing a persistent map between
  OpenStack key and Gnocchi key.
* may raise awareness about the value of using UUIDs everywhere

Change-Id: Ibfc58d6f239a0474cbb3ccd9a6229393ada77e8f
Related-Bug: #1480346
'}]
commit_message:
Introduce a resource id translation shim

In the openstack environment resource ids are a mismash of UUIDs
(yay!) and other things (boo!). When gnocchi receives a resource id
that is not a UUID, it drops it on the floor with a 400 error.

In some sense this is the exact right thing to do. In others it is
entirely impractical given the use context.

This change introduces a shim which accepts any string as a resource
id, either in the URL or in the Resource voluptuous Schema and does
a transformation on it to turn it into a UUID. That transformation
is:

* check if the string <= 255 in length (ValueError if not)
* create a uuid5 using RESOURCE_ID_NAMESPACE UUID and the string
* use the resulting UUID as the local id for the resource

This is a recommended form of creating URNs via rfc 4122
https://www.ietf.org/rfc/rfc4122.txt

The transform is done for both writes and reads. This is necessary
because we have no control over who or what is the the caller using
the API. Gnocchi users will expect to be able to access data in the
Gnocchi API by the IDs they are familiar with.

Doing things this way:

* keeps UUIDs as the primary identifiers internally
* requires no indexer-database migration (which a change in id
  structure would).
* is less intrusive than providing a persistent map between
  OpenStack key and Gnocchi key.
* may raise awareness about the value of using UUIDs everywhere

Change-Id: Ibfc58d6f239a0474cbb3ccd9a6229393ada77e8f
Related-Bug: #1480346

commit_message:
Return complete response from flavors_client part-2

Currently compute flavors_client returns Response by removing
top key from Response.
For example-
return service_client.ResponseBody(resp, body['flavor_access'])

As service clients are in direction to move to Tempest-lib, all
service clients should return Response without any truncation.
One good example is Resource pagination links which are lost with current
way of return value. Resource pagination links are present in parallel
(not inside) to top key of Response.

This patch makes flavor-access/extra-specs methods of compute flavors_client
to return complete Response body.

Implements: blueprint method-return-value-and-move-service-clients-to-lib

Change-Id: Id153ba7b5ff838532fd7bf0e2b72815141c2e250

commit_message:
Return complete response from tenant_usages_client

Currently compute tenant_usages_client returns Response by
removing top key from Response.
For example-
 return service_client.ResponseBody(resp, body['tenant_usage'])

As service clients are in direction to move to Tempest-lib, all
service clients should return Response without any truncation.
One good example is Resource pagination links which are lost with current
way of return value. Resource pagination links are present in parallel
(not inside) to top key of Response.

This patch makes compute tenant_usages_client to return
complete Response body.

Change-Id: I0e6287b1a720d5f3f129fcaa8c08cf6d40abf8e8
Implements: blueprint method-return-value-and-move-service-clients-to-lib

way of return value. Resource pagination links are present in parallel
(not inside) to top key of Response.

This patch makes compute services_client to return
complete Response body.

commit_message:
Make models_v2 explicitly import rbac_db_models

The Network model was implicitly relying on a core plugin to import
the db_base_plugin_v2 module which would import the rbac model module
so "NetworkRBAC" would be defined by the time something would query
the DB. However, this isn't the case for scripts or agents that are
importing models_v2 and trying to query the DB directly so they will
now break with an sqlaclhemy error about a missing model.

This patch makes models_v2 import the rbac_db_models module directly
so the model will always be defined.

This would have resulted in a circular import because the
rbac_db_models module required the HasId and HasTenant classes
in models_v2. So this patch also moves these helper classes
into model_base.

Change-Id: I338ce1c0ba55647e6410a63f937737f75a63057d
Closes-Bug: #1488032

revisions:
[{'number': 3, 'created': '2015-08-05 13:45:11.000000000', 'files': ['trove/db/sqlalchemy/session.py'], 'message': 'Do not cache the SQLAlchemy session

The Trove SQLAlchemy handler caches the session. This should not be done
for multi-threaded apps:
http://docs.sqlalchemy.org/en/rel_1_0/orm/contextual.html

I noticed this when bringing up a cluster. The conductor receives
multiple heartbeats in a short span of time and the shared session
causes an out of sync exception.

The fix is to create a new session whenever it is needed, instead of
accessing a cached version.

Change-Id: I94da76e0a9080f0d2dd287eae0e1d5b23d1ade2e
Closes-bug: #1481493'}]
commit_message:
Do not cache the SQLAlchemy session

The Trove SQLAlchemy handler caches the session. This should not be done
for multi-threaded apps:
http://docs.sqlalchemy.org/en/rel_1_0/orm/contextual.html

I noticed this when bringing up a cluster. The conductor receives
multiple heartbeats in a short span of time and the shared session
causes an out of sync exception.

The fix is to create a new session whenever it is needed, instead of
accessing a cached version.

Change-Id: I94da76e0a9080f0d2dd287eae0e1d5b23d1ade2e
Closes-bug: #1481493

commit_message:
Fix RBAC filters

'index' isn't a valid filter term, and both the glance plugins try to
use it as one, which causes queries to fail for non-admin users. Patch
changes the RBAC filters to use an 'indices' filter which first
restricts on index and then applies the rbac filters and the query.

Change-Id: I35d2703fbb84e1b89e76dee842bb2416a90a999d
Closes-Bug: #1484285

 tox -epy34 <my-test>

commit_message:
Allow py34 to run tests individually

Prior to this patch, when I do:

 tox -epy34 <my-test>

the argument is ignored and all whitelisted tests are executed.
This is not in line with the other testenv's. This patch ensures
that posargs are processed if available, and that we fall back on
the lot of tests when not specified.

Change-Id: I176d7bba690b1c7e0c64d11528d9c851472b503b

subject: Don't try to get aodh endpoint if auth_url didn't provided
revisions:
[{'number': 2, 'created': '2015-08-25 01:32:56.000000000', 'files': ['ceilometerclient/tests/unit/test_client.py', 'ceilometerclient/v2/client.py'], 'message': "Don't try to get aodh endpoint if auth_url didn't provided

This change includes:

* Allow users of ceilometerclient specifying aodh_endpoint explicitly
* If aodh_endpoint didn't provided and users just provide ceilometer
  endpoint and token, no auth_url, we assume aodh is unavailable and
  avoid trying to get aodh endpoint.

Change-Id: Idd0ce60058d23507a99b89926e461d19db267ca2
Closes-Bug: #1488290
"}]
commit_message:
Don't try to get aodh endpoint if auth_url didn't provided

This change includes:

* Allow users of ceilometerclient specifying aodh_endpoint explicitly
* If aodh_endpoint didn't provided and users just provide ceilometer
  endpoint and token, no auth_url, we assume aodh is unavailable and
  avoid trying to get aodh endpoint.

Change-Id: Idd0ce60058d23507a99b89926e461d19db267ca2
Closes-Bug: #1488290

commit_message:
LeftHand driver is ignoring reserved_percentage

The LH driver was hard coding the reserved_percentage parameter to 0.
The LeftHand driver should be reading this value from the cinder
configuration file as it's used in the capacity filter for calculating
capacities.

DocImpact

Change-Id: Ib76c191f75300f9607811727b0f08ed09deb06c0
Closes-Bug: 1486267

subject: Trap formatting errors
revisions:
[{'number': 4, 'created': '2015-08-24 13:28:05.000000000', 'files': ['oslo_i18n/tests/test_message.py', 'oslo_i18n/_message.py'], 'message': "Trap formatting errors

Trap errors when trying to use translated messages as format strings so
translations don't break applications. Log the error, with the format
string (without interpolated values) and the original message so a bug
report can include it to make fixing the translation easier.

Co-Authored-By: Doug Hellmann <doug@doughellmann.com>

Change-Id: I5c711b4654b5b2e591bcf365401ff35f7224fe82
Closes-bug: #1339337
"}]
commit_message:
Trap formatting errors

Trap errors when trying to use translated messages as format strings so
translations don't break applications. Log the error, with the format
string (without interpolated values) and the original message so a bug
report can include it to make fixing the translation easier.

Co-Authored-By: Doug Hellmann <doug@doughellmann.com>

Change-Id: I5c711b4654b5b2e591bcf365401ff35f7224fe82
Closes-bug: #1339337

commit_message:
Enable HAProxy Stats Web UI

This patch enables the HAProxy webstats for all the configures
backends and frontends.

A password entry is added to user_secrets.yml for the webstats
password.

It also adds variables for port number, username and password
which can be overridden in user_variables.yml appropriately.

Change-Id: Iec866ad124bec6fb0b8524a966adf64e22422035
Closes-Bug: #1446432

commit_message:
Clear cached os-client auth on unauthorized

Uses a decorator around glance's 'serialize' functions to purge the
openstack client cache on Unauthorized failures, forcing a re-auth.

This issue needs addressing more fully as a separate BP.

Change-Id: I1077f1e82099ffaa90966fbf050700a8a0075394
Closes-Bug: #1417878

revisions:
[{'number': 6, 'created': '2015-08-23 15:26:53.000000000', 'files': ['zuul/layout.yaml'], 'message': 'puppet: run openstack-integration jobs for keystone & oslib modules

puppet-openstack-integration jobs are now working:
* Keystone is deployed in WSGI with Puppet modules (keystone &
  openstacklib are the two biggest requirements)
* Tempest is run to validate Keystone v2 and v3 APIs.

Now, we could like to move forward and add the jobs for puppet-keystone
and puppet-openstacklib so we can see how it behaves with Puppet
modules.

In short-term, we would like to get the feedback from the jobs and see if
it needs more adjustment.
In medium-term, we might want to add the jobs to other modules
(puppet-nova, etc).
In long-term, openstack-integration jobs will deploy a full OpenStack
setup, single node first, probably multi-node one day.

Depends-On: I4b8f7fa7a694743758ea2073b532184c587899d1
Change-Id: Id88de8eaccea9051138f03a93ff7e23135262ee7
'}]
commit_message:
puppet: run openstack-integration jobs for keystone & oslib modules

puppet-openstack-integration jobs are now working:
* Keystone is deployed in WSGI with Puppet modules (keystone &
  openstacklib are the two biggest requirements)
* Tempest is run to validate Keystone v2 and v3 APIs.

Now, we could like to move forward and add the jobs for puppet-keystone
and puppet-openstacklib so we can see how it behaves with Puppet
modules.

In short-term, we would like to get the feedback from the jobs and see if
it needs more adjustment.
In medium-term, we might want to add the jobs to other modules
(puppet-nova, etc).
In long-term, openstack-integration jobs will deploy a full OpenStack
setup, single node first, probably multi-node one day.

Depends-On: I4b8f7fa7a694743758ea2073b532184c587899d1
Change-Id: Id88de8eaccea9051138f03a93ff7e23135262ee7

commit_message:
Cap cryptography to less than 1.0

Cryptography 1.0 released Aug 12, 2015 at about 13:38 utc (if my
timezone converstion is correct).

A fresh run of devstack at 05:26 utc on Aug 13, 2015 failed:
http://paste.openstack.org/show/412820/ This experiment was
undertaken after some reports of some third party ci systems
failing.

The new cryptography release is suspected. This is a preemptive
cap to try to avoid the gate going boom.

Change-Id: I11101be9a650def8e58f17ef0b3b8ae1b98e2c39
Depends-On: I655d84f3c679d6a29c84879facbe6f3d31f2c3ad

commit_message:
Cap cryptography to less than 1.0

Cryptography 1.0 released Aug 12, 2015 at about 13:38 utc (if my
timezone converstion is correct).

A fresh run of devstack at 05:26 utc on Aug 13, 2015 failed:
http://paste.openstack.org/show/412820/ This experiment was
undertaken after some reports of some third party ci systems
failing.

The new cryptography release is suspected. This is a preemptive
cap to try to avoid the gate going boom.

Needed-By: I11101be9a650def8e58f17ef0b3b8ae1b98e2c39
Change-Id: I655d84f3c679d6a29c84879facbe6f3d31f2c3ad

commit_message:
Move common sample files methods in test base class

As functional tests have been shared among v2 and v2.1, some
function to get sample files present in api_samples_test_base.py
are now unused.

This commits removes those unused functions and moves the
correct one from  api_sample_base.py to api_samples_test_base.py.

Partially implements blueprint test-collapse-v2-and-v21

commit_message:
Share server POST sample file for microversion too

There are many place where server POST request has been used to tests
other API behavior. There was issue of having duplicate
server POST req and resp sample files in each API sample directory.
we added logic to share those sample files from common place
('servers' sample dir)

As microversion tests also need to share such logic, This commit
extends that logic to work for microversion tests also.

Partially implements blueprint test-collapse-v2-and-v21

Change-Id: I3448e1934585c2dabed6c45216ea0513db258b27

commit_message:
Merge limits functional tests of v2 and v2.1

Currently v2 and v2.1 have separate functional tests and their
corresponding sample files. As v2 and v2.1 are supposed to be identical,
there is overhead to maintain two set of functional tests and sample files.
We can have one set of tests which can run for both v2 and v2.1.

This commit merges limits functional tests.
There was no functional tests for limits in v2.1

V2 implied RateLimitingMiddleware while V2.1 does not have that
so the response data is different between V2 and V2.1,
there are more info in "rate" section in V2 than V2.1.
We have to keep both of the template files.

Partially implements blueprint test-collapse-v2-and-v21

Change-Id: If4fbaaeaa1819083f7f4c460216023ae8f65021d

commit_message:
Merge used-limits functional tests of v2 and v2.1

Currently v2 and v2.1 have separate functional tests and their
corresponding sample files. As v2 and v2.1 are supposed to be identical,
there is overhead to maintain two set of functional tests and sample files.
We can have one set of tests which can run for both v2 and v2.1.

This commit merges used_limits functional tests.

V2 implied RateLimitingMiddleware while V2.1 dropped that from
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/115893/, so the response data is
different between V2 and V2.1, there are more info in "rate" section in
V2 than V2.1. We have to keep both of the template files.

Partially implements blueprint test-collapse-v2-and-v21

Change-Id: I3192f550b57694ccb700eebcc0af55468a2f222f

commit_message:
Enable configurable index names

The 'enabled plugin' interface now returns a resource type to plugin
mapping so that the internal details of indexing are less tied to the
API, and specifically so that Elasticsearch index names are configurable
without requiring clients to be aware of it.

The elasticsearch doc type is NOT expected to be configurable, for the
reason that there seems no compelling reason to allow it; for that
reason, 'type' should uniquely identify a plugin (and it's suggested
that be the openstack identifier for a resource). In the event that this
changes, 'resource_type' is currently a pseudonym for 'type' in the
search API btu could be expanded in plugin implementations to fully
abstract away the elasticsearch doc type.

Changes the glance plugin index name to 'searchlight'.

Change-Id: Ibf562df1c3cc6b0c17ee65886641cfa9e6468d5e
Implements: blueprint dont-expose-index-doctype

commit_message:
Remove context usage from driver layer

We actually don't need RequestContext when talking with other
openstack services using sdk. Therefore, this patch removes context
usage from driver layer. Now a credential dictionary will be used
to invoke creation_connection method of sdk driver.

Change-Id: Icbf753c63cd599a32a263edef8f664885755d08c

when the script is unable to connect to Docker because it's not
running.

commit_message:
Revert "Limit parallel live migrations in progress"

This reverts commit 2c0a306632351fd5bf35ff0ec3f0a133fbe8f1ac.

In that commit, we introduce new status for migration object. As
the os-migrations API will expose this new status also. As the
describe in http://docs.openstack.org/developer/nova/api_microversion_dev.html
we need new microversion when add new status for a resource.

Change-Id: I0e8bfdbefdc8b54862fe5d3910cf98ae0c53deb0

subject: Object store get sending bad headers
revisions:
[{'number': 2, 'created': '2015-08-25 10:52:07.000000000', 'files': ['openstack/tests/unit/object_store/v1/test_obj.py', 'openstack/object_store/v1/obj.py'], 'message': 'Object store get sending bad headers

The get command for Object was sending all the headers and
most of the headers it was sending were related to the last
transaction.  This caused Swift to blow up sometimes and it
makes no sense.  I created bug #1488269 to fix this properly
to send the correct headers.

Change-Id: Id4d4ed65605e1e71bc655d78b62c186379ee3386
'}]
commit_message:
Object store get sending bad headers

The get command for Object was sending all the headers and
most of the headers it was sending were related to the last
transaction.  This caused Swift to blow up sometimes and it
makes no sense.  I created bug #1488269 to fix this properly
to send the correct headers.

Change-Id: Id4d4ed65605e1e71bc655d78b62c186379ee3386

commit_message:
Fixes Nova network manager DHCP server behavior

This fixes bug #1456321. When creating multiple networks at once via
nova-manage network create, the DHCP server for all created networks
would be the gateway IP of the first network. This modifies that
behavior so that the DHCP server for each network is the same as the
gateway IP (dhcp_server can still be explicitly provided, which will
override this behavior).

Change-Id: I31022213e8a023bf01453c346fe78b4faf6bbdd5
Closes-Bug: 1456321

commit_message:
Set an explicit FixedIPs: [] on the Redis VIP

This is to work around an issue with recent Heat code where
the nested stack default for FixedIPs is showing up as a {}
instead of [] which causes heat to fail. No harm in passing
it in explicitly while we look into it.

Change-Id: I2a955c66a0f787e17cc8087e7698e93f02b87dd3
Related-bug: #1486778

commit_message:
Support all_tenants search_opts for neutron

Add support for the all_tenants search option when listing
security group with neutron as the backend

The neutron doesn't have `all-tenants` concept. All the security
groups will be returned if the project/tenant id is not passed.

Change-Id: I465c946a006aca21b298f8226f55725a8c36c1f8
Co-authored-by: Xurong Yang <yangxurong@huawei.com>
closes-bug: #1284202

commit_message:
Revert "Migrate ObjectListBase to subclass from the Oslo one"

This creates a dependency on the oslo_versionedobjects registry,
which has not properly been made yet. Since 0.8.0 makes a change
that assumes the registry is being used properly, this suddenly
breaks. For now, revert this change to keep all the list object
code local and avoid this issue.

This reverts commit 3b08da311447289d60fb900dc69dff0fd004ca17.

Change-Id: Ib1649ce2e7d99533935d62620e9c809d8e4ee8b5
Closes-Bug: #1488270

commit_message:
Rename package to fuel-target-centos-images6.6

To support several Centos versions we need
both Centos6.5 and Centos6.6 images to be
in place. But during master node upgrade
we update fuel-target-centos-images package
and Centos6.5 images disappear. The case is
the same as for fuel-library.

Change-Id: I5b974593d2375bcc6367322fcf182f3dcc006d05
Closes-Bug: #1485527

Implements: blueprint event-alarm-evaluator
"}]
commit_message:
Make event-alarm evaluator caching alarms

This patch enables event-alarm evaluator to cache alarms per project
when it get those alarms from the DB. So the evaluator won't access the
DB while the cache exists and does not expired. Cached alarms will be
updated when the alarm fired for consistency.

'event_alarm_cache_ttl' is added to config.

DocImpact

Change-Id: I4e6aa14947cf060c44e82c5f43dc02be586eb855
Implements: blueprint event-alarm-evaluator

commit_message:
Refactor angular cloud services utilities

A nova-extensions and settings-service services and directives
were implemented at the very end of Kilo.

The directive implementation required a dependency tree that
should have to be maintained.  This removes that dependency
tree. It also greatly improves the ability to customize
the directives, while improving readability, by using the
angular.extend way of creating directives from a template.

Ultimately, this leads to much better decoupling of the
functionality which makes it easier for future plugins
and deployers to write their own directives with similar
functionality.

This is the recommended way by angular docs.
See the bottom of this page for more on extending directives:

  https://github.com/angular/angular.js/wiki/Understanding-Directives

This change also enables the directive to be attribute based,
rather than element based, making it more flexible in usage.

In addition, this takes advantage of compilation that improves
performance by ensuring that non-enabled features are not
compiled, meaning any nested directives will not be processed.

To manually test this with Launch Instance NG:

hz-settings-toggle:
  In local_settings.py the following between True and False
     'can_set_mount_point': True,

  On the first step of Launch Instance, notice that when you select
  Create New Volume that when the above is True, that you'll have
  and input box for setting the device name.  When it is false,
  you won't have the input box.

hz-nova-extensions:
  In openstack_dashboard/dashboards/project/static/dashboard/
     project/workflow/launch-instance/configuration/configuration.html

  Find <div hz-nova-extensions='["ConfigDrive"]'>
  Change to <div hz-nova-extensions='["NON_EXISTENT_EXTENSION"]'>

  Launch the Launch Instance NG. Go to the Configuration step.
  Note that when the extension is ConfigDrive, you'll see the
  checkbox for config drive.  When you set NON_EXISTENT_EXTENSION,
  the checkbox won't exist.

Change-Id: I56b52288d18a2558d2a60878c88714d2672bf783
Partial-Bug: #1450150
Co-Authored-By: Rajat Vig <rajatv@thoughtworks.com>

commit_message:
libvirt: refactor _create_domain_setup_lxc to use Image.get_model

Instead of trying to figure out what the proper ImageModel is for
the instance's image, just use the get_model function. The resulting
ImageModel will actually represent the proper ImageModel for the
instance, and downstream mounting functions will be able to make
intelligent decisions on how to mount the instance's disks.

It is not possible to use get_model for an instance booted from volume,
but we can still use LocalBlockImage in it's case because it is
simply exposed as a block device.

Partial-Bug: #1287754
Change-Id: I0f4456731c9d6f64affbf6924f4a7a4c34df4fd1

commit_message:
Fix 500 for bogus Range request to 0-byte object.

The proxy was trying to pop a byterange off a Range header that didn't
contain syntactically-valid byteranges. This worked about as well as
you'd expect. Now we detect the bogus value and remove the header
entirely.

Change-Id: I24b92f900d33ec79880c7db2870378489d5a6810

object. Remove handle_delete() and refactor check_delete_complete() to
avoid passing rich objects.

Closes-Bug: #1486464

commit_message:
Add jsonpath-rw-ext to global requirements

This new extension module to jsonpath-rw is
required by ceilometer module to handle jsonpath
querying and expression evaluations.

This new library satisfies most requirements
in README as follows:

This library is:

* is actively maintained
* is good code
* is compatible with py3
* is licensed under Apache
* is not yet packaged in the distros. We will
  look into that next.
* This library has features that are not yet covered
  under other libraries in global requirements.

Change-Id: I4ebf773fd8e01185d3d1946c971d98f5c15e610a

commit_message:
Integration tests no longer rely on entities' display names in tables

Avoid this because display names can be truncated (UX feature) and
that makes integration tests fragile. Instead for the cells which
have truncated contents store original contents in 'data-selenium'
attribute and check this attribute first in tests.

Implements blueprint: integration-tests-hardening

commit_message:
Add HOST_USERNAME existence check

This change adds a $HOST_USERNAME existence check to
fedra/ubuntu-guest elements.

This will help provide feedback to users who build an image manually
based on doc/source/dev/building_guest_images.rst.

commit_message:
Adding shared and protected resources support

Adding shared across tenants and protected from modifictaion
resources support. Implemented for clusters, cluster templates,
node group templates, data sources, job executions, jobs,
job binaries and job binary internals.

Changes:
* Added validation checks to service.validations.acl
* Changed validation schema's to support "is_public"
  and "is_protected" fields
* Added validation of "is_protected" field for update(scale/cancel)
  and delete methods of corresponding resources
* Extended get and list methods outputs with "is_public" resources
* Added unit tests for "is_public" and "is_protected" resources

Change-Id: I1a3cb14b8de70256e6aa27312dde341e85fc376c
Partially-Implements: blueprint shared-protected-resources

commit_message:
Move "versions" functional tests in v2.1 tests

This commit moves "versions" functional tests in v2.1 tests which are
under /v3 directory and run those for v2 and v2.1.

There was no tests for v2.1 version so this patch adds
tests for v2.1 version request.

Partially implements blueprint test-collapse-v2-and-v21

commit_message:
Added karma threshold reporting & failure

This patch adds unit test coverage threshold reporting, adding
statement, branch, function, and line coverage to the console
output in infra, and failing the build if the threshold has not
been met.

The threshold values have been set to the current observed
coverage values - future patches should update this up as
coverage improves.

Closes-Bug: 1487109
Change-Id: Ie83ebf5d976b3538e3528787b05de3e83df18af8

commit_message:
Move CPU and RAM allocation ratios to ResourceTracker

In order to have a per-compute allocation ratio basis, we need to provide those
to the compute nodes, so let's provide them there and import them on the
scheduler side until the work is fully completed.

That change specifically implies that nova.conf is consistent across the whole
cloud since what was formerly defined on the scheduler side will have its
definition by the compute nodes.

Release notes for Liberty are already updated to mention the above.

Change-Id: Ic2a80b3804fc27f655e6e74c30f09cab59b16ccb
Partially-Implements: blueprint allocation-ratio-to-resource-tracker

commit_message:
Substitute bdms specified with the same name

If a user specifies several bdms with the same name, the last specified
bdm should only be considered. This affects all API's methods having bdm
list in parameters.

commit_message:
Ability run run Nova API under /compute

Nova API now has an additional /compute in its url
with devstack change:
Ic84b5c0dc0726662470ef9c076a0cadca55a3917

This causes failure in the CI job that runs Nova API
under Apache as remove_version_from_href wrongly assumes
that /v2 or /v1.1 etc is the beginning of the path
component of the url. We need to be able to tolerate
that /compute may occur before v2 or v1.1 etc.

Partial-Bug: #216048
Change-Id: If4a428d948bcc85e4b97ced3fb5d135715dd836c

commit_message:
Graceful ovs-agent restart

When agent is restarted it drops all existing flows. This
breaks all networking until the flows are re-created.

This change adds an ability to drop only old flows.
Agent_uuid_stamp is added for agents. This agent_uuid_stamp is set as
cookie for flows and then flows with stale cookies are deleted during
cleanup.

Co-Authored-By: Ann Kamyshnikova<akamyshnikova@mirantis.com>

Closes-bug: #1383674

DocImpact

Change-Id: I95070d8218859d4fff1d572c1792cdf6019dd7ea

commit_message:
Add pagination support for executions query API

Add query params for action list REST API:

* limit: return a maximun number of items at a time, default is None, the
  query result will include all the resource items, which is backward
  compatible.

* marker: the ID of the last item in the previous list.

* sort_keys: columns to sort results by. Default: created_at, which is
  backward compatible.

* sort_dirs: directions to sort corresponding to sort_keys, "asc" or
  "desc" can be choosed. Default: desc. The length of sort_dirs can
  be equal or less than that of sort_keys.

Change-Id: I2fcca2a5589936d24aa52245a686115598fbd858
Partially-Implements: blueprint mistral-pagination-support

The os.system call returns an exit status on Unix systems that is
similar to the os.wait command. This format is a 16-bit number whose
lower byte is the signal number that killed the process and the higher
byte is the exit status. This caused errors in the way that the scenario
runner script returned the exit status of the scenario test.

To fix this issue, the runner has been modified to use subprocess.call
in favor of os.system. This solution should be portable across operating

Closes-Bug: 1486493
'}]
commit_message:
Changing scenario runner to use subprocess

The os.system call returns an exit status on Unix systems that is
similar to the os.wait command. This format is a 16-bit number whose
lower byte is the signal number that killed the process and the higher
byte is the exit status. This caused errors in the way that the scenario
runner script returned the exit status of the scenario test.

To fix this issue, the runner has been modified to use subprocess.call
in favor of os.system. This solution should be portable across operating
systems while maintaining the expected functionality.

Change-Id: Iea95312702977a5f2a194397abf214ae20c2e23d
Closes-Bug: 1486493

commit_message:
Add schema for additional properties of BaseListSpec

Exception should be raised for creation of workflow such as:

---
version: '2.0'
name: which_should_not_appear
wf:
  type: direct
  tasks:
    task1: std.echo output='hello, world.'

For jsonschema, If additionalProperties is an object, that object is a
schema that will be used to validate any additional properties not listed
in properties.

Change-Id: I11a0e514f525a1ce278bdbf69d001a6249ef2183
Closes-Bug: #1442128

commit_message:
Add manila nfs data sources

This change will allow data sources with urls of the form
"manila://share-id/path", similar to manila urls for job binaries.
The Sahara native url will be logged in the JobExecution, but
the true runtime url (file:///mnt/path) for manila shares will
be used in the cluster.

Partial-implements: blueprint manila-as-a-data-source
Change-Id: I0b43491decbe6cb0ec0b84314cf9b407b9e3fb4a

commit_message:
pep8: Fix usage of the l10n _('...') function

Fix the pep8 warning H702 "Formatting operation should be outside of
localization method call".

For the logger, pass parameters as indexed parameters instead of using
the string str%args operator, the logger is more reliable in case of
formatting error.

Change-Id: If418bc155f6a6c0a00f63e3d87ebe4addf4aae55

commit_message:
Adding sessions module and keystone client upgrade

This change implements the sahara.service.sessions module with the basic
session cache object. It also adds the authentication plugin from the
keystonemiddleware into the context for rest transactions.

It also migrates the keystone client utility functions to use the new
session methodology. The trust module has been accordingly fixed to make
greater use of authentication objects instead of client objects.

* adding auth plugin to context
* adding sessions module
* adding test for sessions
* adding keystonemiddleware base auth plugin object to context on api
  call
* adding keystone session to sessions module
* refactoring keystone client to use sessions
* adding keystone methods to retrieve auth plugins, tokens, and service
  catalog
* changing sahara.service.trusts to use new keystone methods
* fixing trust tests to fit new authentication methodologies

Change-Id: I65ed4b4dcee8752bf4e66ef9e47305ff408d8d5d
Partial-Implements: bp keystone-sessions

commit_message:
Return complete resp from security_groups_client

Currently compute security_groups_client returns Response by
removing top key from Response.
For example-
 return service_client.ResponseBody(resp, body['security_group'])

As service clients are in direction to move to Tempest-lib, all
service clients should return Response without any truncation.
One good example is Resource pagination links which are lost with current
way of return value. Resource pagination links are present in parallel
(not inside) to top key of Response.

This patch makes compute security_groups_client to return
complete Response body.

Change-Id: I8cfd1845be221ae2e3629cc79ab5fdfd14ac48d4
Implements: blueprint method-return-value-and-move-service-clients-to-lib

Currently we rely on an internal implementation detail of the
server resource to validate, which is both potentially fragile
and also inflexible should you wish to override the server
resource with a nested stack resource.

Instead, check the expected value exists within the properties
of the resource, which decouples the two resource implementations
and potentially enables easier overriding of the server resource,

Change-Id: Id666f7ae951b4ed31930f09fe0c1b0d8c3fe09ed
'}]
commit_message:
SoftwareDeployments modify validation to use properties

Currently we rely on an internal implementation detail of the
server resource to validate, which is both potentially fragile
and also inflexible should you wish to override the server
resource with a nested stack resource.

Instead, check the expected value exists within the properties
of the resource, which decouples the two resource implementations
and potentially enables easier overriding of the server resource,
e.g with a nested stack for testing.

Change-Id: Id666f7ae951b4ed31930f09fe0c1b0d8c3fe09ed

subject: Fix trueorfalse call in tempest use accounts check
revisions:
[{'number': 1, 'created': '2015-08-25 01:23:04.000000000', 'files': ['lib/tempest'], 'message': "Fix trueorfalse call in tempest use accounts check

The lib/tempest variable definition for TEMPEST_USE_TEST_ACCOUNTS was
incorrectly calling the trueorfalse function by passing the variable's
value to the function instead of the variable's name. This was causing
trueorfalse the default value of false to always be returned even when
specifying the option as true in the localrc. (well assuming True or
it's variants wasn't an actual defined variable with a value that
would return true) This commit fixes this issue by properly using the
trueorfalse function.

Change-Id: I8cefb58f49dcd2cb2def8a5071d0892af520e7f7
"}]
commit_message:
Fix trueorfalse call in tempest use accounts check

The lib/tempest variable definition for TEMPEST_USE_TEST_ACCOUNTS was
incorrectly calling the trueorfalse function by passing the variable's
value to the function instead of the variable's name. This was causing
trueorfalse the default value of false to always be returned even when
specifying the option as true in the localrc. (well assuming True or
it's variants wasn't an actual defined variable with a value that
would return true) This commit fixes this issue by properly using the
trueorfalse function.

Change-Id: I8cefb58f49dcd2cb2def8a5071d0892af520e7f7

subject: Use default exchange for reply queue
revisions:
[{'number': 7, 'created': '2015-05-05 08:40:02.000000000', 'files': ['oslo_messaging/_drivers/impl_rabbit.py'], 'message': "Use default exchange for reply queue

DNOT MERGE: this doesn't allow smooth upgrade

For replies amqp specification recommands to use the default exchange instead.
See bug report for more details.

This change introduce a new configuration option to allow
operators to deprecated legacy topology before we do it, to avoid to creates
unless exchanges queues once they are finished to migrate to the new topology
version (rabbit_topology_backward_compatibility) .

Closes-bug: #1437951
Change-Id: Id207553987b169e9e7918113bfddbab2e3bad5c4
"}]
commit_message:
Use default exchange for reply queue

DNOT MERGE: this doesn't allow smooth upgrade

For replies amqp specification recommands to use the default exchange instead.
See bug report for more details.

This change introduce a new configuration option to allow
operators to deprecated legacy topology before we do it, to avoid to creates
unless exchanges queues once they are finished to migrate to the new topology
version (rabbit_topology_backward_compatibility) .

Closes-bug: #1437951
Change-Id: Id207553987b169e9e7918113bfddbab2e3bad5c4

commit_message:
Streaming of all reports archive implemented

For providing all reports at once we generate, archive them
and transmit as single file.
Generation and archiving of all reports can take long time
and cause http server connection timeout error.
For preventing such errors used lazy reports generation
and on-the-fly data streming without saving they into files.

- tar archive used instead zip
- streaming of tar archive implemented

Change-Id: I8a71c462cf6ad61ef5b5798770d140866d36edb1
Closes-Bug: #1487356

commit_message:
[EDP]enable recurrence edp job in sahara

currently, sahara only support one-time click run edp job, but
some times we should run recurrence edp jobs, for example, from
8:00AM to 9:00AM, run this job every 5 mins.

Change-Id: Icb7203e2e584894408fe7617ce25cc570f272deb
Implements bp: recurrence-edp-job

commit_message:
Fix wrong argument name in _rpc_update_firewall

Passing id (built-in function id) instead of firewall_id to
get_firewall_routers caused DBErrors due to wrong argument type.

This change fixes this typo and adds missing unit tests that can
prevent such error from appearing in the future.

Change-Id: I35f13b1aab5a566c1e2768a4027e61120bf6ba2e
Closes-Bug: #1475244

commit_message:
Indexes added on action_logs.body

For increasing speed of creating clusters report indexes on
body->>'action_name' and body->>'action_type' were added.
Query execution plan cost was optimized from 21000 to 60.

Collector base DB test fixed. Alembic constant 'base' used
for downgrade all alembic migrations instead of current
revisions number calculation.

Change-Id: Ief06aa9bbb94ebad2c2791617df8fb96cf979118
Closes-Bug: #1488092

subject: Add disable_custom_constraints option
revisions:
[{'number': 1, 'created': '2015-08-24 16:02:45.000000000', 'files': ['heat/tests/test_environment.py', 'heat/engine/environment.py', 'heat/engine/constraint/common_constraints.py', 'heat/common/config.py'], 'message': 'Add disable_custom_constraints option

Adds a global option which forces all custom contraints validation
to pass (both resource properties and paramters which reference custom
constraints in templates).

In future it might be nice to offer the option of only disabling the
properties validation, as this is the only part which the user can't
control via the template or other user-facing interfaces.

The use-case here is to enable easier "stubbing" of resources, such
as replacing an OS::Nova::Server with a dummy server nested stack,
then combining that nested stack with an OS::Heat::SoftwareDeployment.
This will be useful for testing (the metadata of the dummy resource
may be inspected without spinning up an actual server), and also for
certain niche heat use-cases such as applying software config to a
pre-provisioned server.

Change-Id: Iec169d4b872ebed8a99f2847e2cb01267b94fc9a
'}]
commit_message:
Add disable_custom_constraints option

Adds a global option which forces all custom contraints validation
to pass (both resource properties and paramters which reference custom
constraints in templates).

In future it might be nice to offer the option of only disabling the
properties validation, as this is the only part which the user can't
control via the template or other user-facing interfaces.

The use-case here is to enable easier "stubbing" of resources, such
as replacing an OS::Nova::Server with a dummy server nested stack,
then combining that nested stack with an OS::Heat::SoftwareDeployment.
This will be useful for testing (the metadata of the dummy resource
may be inspected without spinning up an actual server), and also for
certain niche heat use-cases such as applying software config to a
pre-provisioned server.

Change-Id: Iec169d4b872ebed8a99f2847e2cb01267b94fc9a

* Eventually it comes to method direct_workflow._has_outbound_tasks()
  that didn't account for cycles because it relied only on task
  specifications rather than actual transitions that triggered. In

Change-Id: I6a21958284da501116253007856595fad7f0670b
"}]
commit_message:
Enabling direct workflow cycles: fixing evaluation of final context

* Eventually it comes to method direct_workflow._has_outbound_tasks()
  that didn't account for cycles because it relied only on task
  specifications rather than actual transitions that triggered. In
  order to calculate actual transitions we just need to find next task
  names based on task execution outbound context and remove engine
  commands.
* Minor style changes and refactoring.

Change-Id: I6a21958284da501116253007856595fad7f0670b

commit_message:
Make tox -e pep8 check for lines being too long

At some point recently tox -e pep8 stopped finding lines
longer than 79 characters. With hacking==0.8 too long lines
were detected, with hacking==0.10.2 they are not.

This change adds E checks to the flake8 select list in tox.ini.
That puts back long line checking but also adds some indenting
checks that have presumably not been made before. So those are
fixed too.

Change-Id: I3fa8c6621d1397457453af609501d00d252a5c8f

subject: Use correct Storage-Policy header for REPLICATE requests
reviewers: [{'_account_id': 3, 'name': 'Jenkins', 'username': 'jenkins'}, {'_account_id': 1179, 'name': 'Clay Gerrard', 'email': 'clay.gerrard@gmail.com', 'username': 'clay-gerrard'}, {'_account_id': 2622, 'name': 'Samuel Merritt', 'email': 'sam@swiftstack.com', 'username': 'torgomatic'}, {'_account_id': 5600, 'name': 'Brian Cline', 'email': 'bcline@softlayer.com', 'username': 'briancline'}, {'_account_id': 7233, 'name': 'Matthew Oliver', 'email': 'matt@oliver.net.au', 'username': 'mattoliverau'}, {'_account_id': 13052, 'name': 'SwiftStack Cluster CI', 'email': 'openstack-ci@swiftstack.com', 'username': 'swiftstack-cluster-ci', 'tags': ['SERVICE_USER']}]
revisions:
[{'number': 2, 'created': '2015-08-24 18:20:43.000000000', 'files': ['swift/obj/replicator.py', 'test/unit/obj/test_replicator.py'], 'message': "Use correct Storage-Policy header for REPLICATE requests

Under some concurrency the object-replicator could potentially send the
wrong X-Backed-Storage-Policy-Index header to it's partner nodes during
replication if there were multiple storage policies on the same node
because of a race where multiple jobs being processed concurrently would
mutate some shared state on the ObjectReplicator instance.

Instead of using shared stated on the ObjectReplicator instance when
mutating the default headers send with REPLICATION requests each job
will copy them into a local where they can safely be updated.

Change-Id: I5522db57af7e308b1f9d4181f14ea14e386a71fd
"}]
commit_message:
Use correct Storage-Policy header for REPLICATE requests

Under some concurrency the object-replicator could potentially send the
wrong X-Backed-Storage-Policy-Index header to it's partner nodes during
replication if there were multiple storage policies on the same node
because of a race where multiple jobs being processed concurrently would
mutate some shared state on the ObjectReplicator instance.

Instead of using shared stated on the ObjectReplicator instance when
mutating the default headers send with REPLICATION requests each job
will copy them into a local where they can safely be updated.

Change-Id: I5522db57af7e308b1f9d4181f14ea14e386a71fd

commit_message:
Adds backend check to setup of LDAP tests

I was finding that by making tweaks in the setup ordering that I was
getting the wrong backends for all (or parts) of a test. This extra
check ensures that I am not making things worse while refactoring.

The way we split setup among inheritance hierarchies makes knowing what
you're getting incredibly difficult.

Change-Id: I025c9a9e89a57bcff0a72cc1e584c3114671b3b3

commit_message:
Retrieve project_id and user_id from context instead of auth_token_info

Currently project_id and user_id are retrieved from auth_token_info in post
method in api layer, but these can be retrieved from auth_token_info['token']
by v3 keystone only. By v2 keystone, it should be auth_token_info['access'].
These parameters can be retrieved from context directly.

Change-Id: Iedbb0e0cc3966dd5ec4720b64176b915af91d592
Closes-Bug: #1487992

commit_message:
Delete deleted_time and url option from webhook-show

URL is not stored in database, so URL will not returned
from server. Only the webhooks which are not deleted can
be shown, so deleted_time is always None in webhook-show.

Change-Id: I318d78983c6f177a1297e5b0ff0146cc01afd281

commit_message:
Remove all traces of oslo incubator

- removes run_tests.sh since it's rarely used and an alternative exists
- removes all the remaining incubator files since nothing uses them

The real value of run_tests.sh over tox is that run_tests.sh enables
running tests against against any virtualenv or Python installation. tox
is just a tool that runs testr commands in a specific virtualenv. testr
can be used directly as a run_tests.sh replacement for running tests in
an arbitrary virtualenv or against any Python installation.

blueprint remove-oslo-incubator
Change-Id: I9d4ef8bf935eb565af1c8d53d1ed71be9a94a975

revisions:
[{'number': 1, 'created': '2015-08-24 13:49:09.000000000', 'files': ['global-requirements.txt'], 'message': 'Updates oslo.service global requirement

The 0.6.0 version of the oslo.service causes services using the
library to stop working on Windows. This affects the nova-compute
service on Windows.

The problem is that it tries access signal.SIGHUP which does not
exist on the Windows platform. This issue was fixed in the commit
with the Change-Id: Id3783160381f4a89e241134ef13c4521a30dfa94 but
it is not released.

oslo.service 0.7.0 deliverable: Ie6bba338ab065aac75323c13cd1dc01b925bd44d

Change-Id: Ib4472a358d79a0f72f6fe0b5fda8bb21b14c0028
'}]
commit_message:
Updates oslo.service global requirement

The 0.6.0 version of the oslo.service causes services using the
library to stop working on Windows. This affects the nova-compute
service on Windows.

The problem is that it tries access signal.SIGHUP which does not
exist on the Windows platform. This issue was fixed in the commit
with the Change-Id: Id3783160381f4a89e241134ef13c4521a30dfa94 but
it is not released.

oslo.service 0.7.0 deliverable: Ie6bba338ab065aac75323c13cd1dc01b925bd44d

Change-Id: Ib4472a358d79a0f72f6fe0b5fda8bb21b14c0028

commit_message:
Revert "mark oslo.vmware as optional dependency"

This reverts commit e67adc385ce6997249fbf70e9402264f758fc6f4.

Adding optional dependency tracking would be nice,
but Cinder is not yet in a place to do this.

- Cinder supports tox 1.6 (minversion in tox.ini)
- This functionality does not work on 1.6, requires 1.7.  Tox
  fails to build a test environment if using tox 1.6.
- We have decided we can't move to tox 1.7 for now.
  ( https://review.openstack.org/#/c/211614/ )

This reverts commit 478e8e970e54aaf3a034dc6347605c1b18291d0d.
- Need to remove oslo.vmware from test-requirements.txt now, as
well.

Closes-Bug: #1484035

Change-Id: Icff52508ff1cd67e8c17964c840d3a5cdcfbbce3

commit_message:
Fix three bugs in webhook related workflows

This patch fixes three bugs in webhook related workflows:
1. Use the senlin service credential with correct trusts as the
   default webhook cred when user didn't provide it explicitly.
2. Translate tenant_id string correctly when generating webhook url.
3. Convert short_id/name of target object to full ID before using
   it to create action;

Change-Id: I3e58ffb4e8dd671426c868561dcf3c17d1b30965
Closes-Bug: #1485864

commit_message:
Return complete response from floating_ips_client

Currently compute floating_ips_client returns Response by removing
top key from Response.
For example-
return service_client.ResponseBody(resp, body['floating_ip'])

As service clients are in direction to move to Tempest-lib, all
service clients should return Response without any truncation.
One good example is Resource pagination links which are lost with current
way of return value. Resource pagination links are present in parallel
(not inside) to top key of Response.

This patch makes compute floating_ips_lient to return complete
Response body.

Implements: blueprint method-return-value-and-move-service-clients-to-lib

Change-Id: Ib11e815a944321589dd618c7696249f0e0eb3938

commit_message:
Return complete response from compute/aggregates_client

Currently compute aggregates_client returns Response by removing
top key from Response.
For example- return service_client.ResponseBody(resp, body['aggregate'])

As service clients are in direction to move to Tempest-lib, all
service clients should return Response without any truncation.
One good example is Resource pagination links which are lost with current
way of return value. Resource pagination links are present in parallel
(not inside) to top key of Response.

This patch makes compute aggregates_client to return complete Response body.

Change-Id: Iac7e2e59b0a5b498fb5be5c7696ebe7bb15be8fe
Implements: blueprint method-return-value-and-move-service-clients-to-lib

commit_message:
Return complete response from instance usage client

Currently compute instance_usage_audit_log_client returns Response by
removing top key from Response.
For example-
 return service_client.ResponseBody(resp, body['instance_usage_audit_log'])

As service clients are in direction to move to Tempest-lib, all
service clients should return Response without any truncation.
One good example is Resource pagination links which are lost with current
way of return value. Resource pagination links are present in parallel
(not inside) to top key of Response.

This patch makes compute instance_usage_audit_log_client to return complete
Response body.

Change-Id: I11038a3b5e263918c150bbb304ae40a905329bef

commit_message:
Make NeutronDbObjectDuplicateEntry exception more verbose

NeutronObjectDuplicateEntry is an exception derived from Conflict,
which is mapped to HTTPConflict. When such exception is thrown
during an API layer call, we will provide more detail to the caller
about what was exactly duplicated, and for which fields,
the information is extracted from the DB exception.

NeutronObjectDuplicateEntry is renamed into NeutronDbObjectDuplicate
to make clear it is for handling db duplicate exceptions, in
the future we could generalize to a base NeutronObjectDuplicate class
if we need separate handling for other object backings (mem, keystore,
etc).

Change-Id: I6ec5883b3456ebc842f3f7bffd8cc924293f5766

commit_message:
Add option to delete Container Secrets

New optional argument "recursive" on both the ContainerManager and
the Container object's delete() functions.
New CLI argument for "container delete": --recursive, -r
Deletes all Secrets in the Container (and the Container itself).

Change-Id: If0f21b1721adf05531d944fd8f1316f084fc6ee5

commit_message:
Several improvements in Rally info

* Change syntax for common queries:
  'rally info BenchmarkScenarios' -> 'rally info find BenchmarkScenarios'

  - for more consistency, also make it more flexible, by supporting multiword
  queries and underscores:

  'rally info find benchmark scenarios'
  'rally info find BenchmarkScenarios'
  'rally info find benchmarkscenarios'
  'rally info find benchmark_scenarios'
  - now output the same thing.

* Reuse cliutils.make_header()
* Output only scenarios in rally.*, ignore plugins etc.
* Update docstrings in the command module

Change-Id: I6756b270d643598c233803b49f635302e14ab467

Add the benchmark Blogbench for the Virtual Machines

Introduce the filesystem benchmark Blogbench [1] that can be used for
measuring the performance of a Virtual Machine by reproducing the load
of a real-world busy file server.

Co-Authored-By: Tzanetos Balitsaris <tzabal@freebsd.org>
Implements: blueprint benchmark-vms
Change-Id: I5a409c44946e88190069f6d3c2032ac1bb1a8f1e

commit_message:
Fix bug to locate hdfs command in HDFS native driver

No longer to locate hdfs command.
Assume the ssh user has the authority to launch hdfs command.
And the user must add hdfs in default PATH manually.

Change-Id: Ia5d118a49ecea092848796067ae48dbead83c40e
Closes-Bug: #1481568

Increase the .durable quorum from 2 to "parity + 1" to guarantee

commit_message:
Quorum on durable response is too low

Increase the .durable quorum from 2 to "parity + 1" to guarantee
that we will never fail to rebuild an object.  Otherwise, with
low durable responses back (< parity + 1), the putter objects
return with failed attribute set to true, thereby failing the
rebuild of fragments for an object.

Change-Id: I80d666f61273e589d0990baa78fd657b3470785d
Closes-Bug: 1484565

commit_message:
ip_lib: support creating Linux dummy interface

This is for use by a DHCP agent interface driver in the
networking-calico project.  networking-calico connects VMs without
using bridging, so it needs an unbridged DHCP port interface with
which it can associate the DHCP subnet prefix, and the Linux dummy
interface (in conjunction with use of Dnsmasq's --bridge-interface
feature) is suitable for that purpose.

Partial-Bug: #1486649
Change-Id: I5485c187bc44bac3c2942c4fc9e5a502912a81a2

commit_message:
libvirt: convert driver to use nova.objects.ImageMeta

Convert the libvirt driver and related files to make use of
the nova.objects.ImageMeta object. Where an image_meta
dict is passed in via the virt API, it is converted to
object form before being used.

Change-Id: If03b166d3ecc3e7fa6b7f1a0c69f8ab1cc7b1972

commit_message:
Moving inline html code out of action-list.spec.js

Currently there are some html code for test hard-coded inside of spec.js
file. It would be much better to move them out to separate html file for
better readability, cleaner spec code. This will also enable the sharing
html mock code between specs.

This patch moves inline html code out of action-list.spec.js.

Change-Id: Id05fbf3948fad3926cc3ecc09e0c95acc84ce41e

commit_message:
Fix link's href to consider osapi_compute_link_prefix

Version show request for both v2 and v2.1 (/v2 and /v2.1) does not
consider the CONF.osapi_compute_link_prefix for buidling links's href.

Above should prepare href using CONF.osapi_compute_link_prefix as done
for other links.

Previously functional tests of specific versions
were not present so it was not caught.

Closes-Bug: 1480009

Change-Id: I54a09d2c56efb0a05832e57313917177b770c8cb

commit_message:
VMware: Delete vmdk UUID during volume detach

During volume attach, the volume vmdk UUID is added to VM's
extra config as a key-value pair "volume-<volume-UUID> =
<volume-vmdk-UUID>". This is required to identify the vmdk
to be removed during volume detach. But the key-value pair
added during volume attach is not deleted during detach.
This patch deletes the relevant key-value pair from VM's
extra config during volume detach.

Closes-Bug: #1477159
Change-Id: Id4d5e2eede5e1d2418f301045fb2b3542a39b471

commit_message:
Reduce the chance of Selenium timeouts in integration tests

Avoid situations when we trying to take something out of a destroyed
box (contents of an element that is no longer there). Plus other
improvements to a couple of element getter functions/predicates that
might had been causing timeouts.

Related-Bug: #1467950
Implements blueprint: integration-tests-hardening

Change-Id: Ia17cb2134eaa5dd14a04384d1b703a8a648f952d

commit_message:
Catch NotFound in format_stack_resource for nested()

If the underlying nested stack doesn't exist for whatever reason,
calling heat resource-list results in a NotFound response even though heat
stack-show confirms the stack exists.

This change catches NotFound when calling resource.nested() in
format_stack_resource.

(cherry-picked and modified from c3f9337c11b78f98704dce9e76e2b74e9098670a)
Change-Id: Iba92d0590561dffb8f902865cc7134b2eddc23ac
Closes-Bug: #1476834
